            <!-- Explanations -->
            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>
                How this construction interiors, envelope &amp; finishes
                calculator works
              </h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed as a compact “databook in calculator form”
                for interior and envelope trades. Instead of separate tools for
                paint, drywall, insulation, siding, roofing and flooring, you
                enter the geometry once and then refine each system with its own
                coverage, waste and cost assumptions.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Geometry and base areas</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>Room / Envelope Geometry</strong> section computes
                three base areas:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Net wall area</strong> (for paint, drywall, interior
                  insulation): perimeter × height − openings.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ceiling area</strong> (for paint, insulation, acoustic
                  finishes): length × width.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Floor area</strong> (for flooring &amp; tile): length
                  × width.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Perimeter</strong> \(P = 2(L + W)\)</p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Gross wall area</strong> \(A_\text{walls,gross} = P
                  \times H\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Net wall area</strong> \(A_\text{walls} =
                  A_\text{walls,gross} - A_\text{openings}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Ceiling / floor area</strong> \(A_\text{ceiling} =
                  A_\text{floor} = L \times W\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Material coverage and waste</h3>
              <p>Each tab uses the same core logic:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Net quantity</strong> \(Q_\text{net} =
                  \dfrac{A_\text{design}}{C}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  where \(A_\text{design}\) is the design area (or volume) and
                  \(C\) is the coverage per unit.
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Quantity incl. waste</strong> \(Q_\text{gross} =
                  Q_\text{net} \times \left(1 + \dfrac{w}{100}\right)\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Cost</strong> \(= Q_\text{gross} \times \text{unit
                  cost}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For discrete items like boards or boxes, the calculator rounds
                <em>up</em> to the next whole unit so you never under‑order.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Typical coverage values (rules of thumb)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interior paint</strong>: 8–12 m²/L per coat on smooth
                  walls.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Drywall boards</strong>: 1.2 × 2.4 m ≈ 2.88 m² per
                  sheet.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Joint compound</strong>: 25–35 m² per bucket for all
                  coats.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Batt insulation</strong>: check pack label; often 8–15
                  m² per pack.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Roofing shingles</strong>: 1 bundle ≈ 3 m² (1 “square”
                  ≈ 9.3 m²).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Flooring / tile</strong>: 1–2 m² per box is common.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>4. Building envelope vs. interiors</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>building envelope</strong> is the boundary between
                inside and outside: roof, exterior walls, windows, doors,
                foundations, air/vapor barriers and cladding. Interior finishes
                (paint, drywall, flooring, ceilings) sit inside this envelope.
              </p>
              <p>Good envelope design manages four key flows:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Heat</strong> (insulation, thermal breaks, low‑U
                  windows).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Air</strong> (air barriers, airtight detailing at
                  joints and penetrations).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Moisture</strong> (vapor control, drainage planes,
                  flashing, ventilation).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Water</strong> (roofing, cladding, sealants,
                  overhangs).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator focuses on <strong>quantities</strong>, but you
                should always cross‑check with the project’s specifications,
                climate zone requirements and manufacturer details for
                performance.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Practical tips for more reliable estimates</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Use <strong>manufacturer coverage data</strong> whenever
                  available instead of generic values.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Increase waste factors for
                  <strong>complex geometries</strong>, diagonal tile layouts, or
                  heavy cutting.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Separate <strong>high‑abuse areas</strong> (corridors,
                  lobbies) from standard rooms if they use different systems.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Export or note down the results per trade to build a
                  consolidated <strong>materials schedule</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

